{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492861"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:47:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:47:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1172"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1172"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.05,0.01,0.11,0.76]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1172"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90554"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1172"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1172"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74772"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"4256"},{"type":"tags","id":"4272"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11627"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5747"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5776"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28922"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29877"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42234"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44696"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90554"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after being rescued from a smoke-filled room in a burning house. The mattress on which he was asleep caught fire and he sustained burns to his face, hands and chest as he struggled his way out of the room. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His burns are judged to be partial thickness and occupy 25% of the total body surface area. His hair and eyebrows are singed and he speaks in a hoarse whisper.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rapid infusion of 2L isotonic saline","Immediate cooling of burns with sterile water","Intravenous hydrocortisone","Nasal high-flow oxygen via a humidified circuit","Endotracheal intubation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs of potential airway compromise following smoke inhalation and burns. The presence of hoarse voice, singed facial hair, and exposure to smoke in an enclosed space are concerning features that suggest impending airway compromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll of the suggested answers are reasonable responses, however, in emergency situations we must remember to follow a DRSABCDE approach to our assessment. In our primary survey, our main concerns are regarding patient airway, breathing and circulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndotracheal intubation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step due to the high risk of progressive airway oedema. Early intubation is safer than waiting for obvious obstruction to develop, as subsequent intubation may become extremely difficult or impossible. Signs suggesting inhalation injury include exposure to fire in an enclosed space, voice changes, facial burns, singed nasal hair, and soot in secretions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid infusion of isotonic saline\u003C/strong\u003E will be necessary for fluid resuscitation in this major burn (\u003E20% total body surface area), but should be initiated after securing the airway, as fluid resuscitation may worsen airway edema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate cooling of burns\u003C/strong\u003E with sterile water is an important early intervention for thermal burns to limit tissue damage, but addressing the compromised airway takes precedence. Cooling can be initiated once the airway is secured.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous hydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in the acute management of burns. There is no evidence that steroids improve outcomes in inhalation injuries, and they may increase the risk of infection. Steroids do not prevent airway edema effectively enough to obviate the need for intubation when signs of airway compromise are present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENasal high-flow oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate in this situation where there is impending airway compromise. While oxygen supplementation is important, it does not address the fundamental problem of potential upper airway obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Airway compromise requiring early intubation in burns patients is indicated by voice changes, facial burns, singed hair, and smoke exposure in an enclosed space.","Burns \u003E20% total body surface area are considered major trauma requiring fluid resuscitation.","In burns patients initial fluid resuscitation should be delayed until after airway is secured to avoid worsening airway oedema."],"references":["Burns Management Guidelines. In: Victorian adult burns service [online]. Available at: https://www.vicburns.org.au/","Greenhalgh DG. Management of Burns. N Engl J Med 2019; 380:2349-59. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31189038/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74772"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1172"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74772"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T11:31:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T11:32:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1172"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90554"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"re